%I A094406 #17 Jul 08 2026 23:57:10
%S A094406 4,2,11,15,5,3,14,45,36,6,112,269,15999
%N A094406 Smallest unhappy number that takes n steps to reach any of the unhappy cycle (4, 16, 37, 58, 89, 145, 42, 20) under iteration of sum of squares of digits map.
%C A094406 This sequence is an analog of sequence A001273 with the unhappy numbers instead of the happy numbers.
%C A094406 The next term, 577999999999....999999999999 (199 digits) is too large to include.
%H A094406 Michel Marcus, <a href="/A094406/b094406.txt">Table of n, a(n) for n = 4..17</a>
%H A094406 Walter Schneider, <a href="http://web.archive.org/web/2004/www.wschnei.de/digit-related-numbers/happy-numbers.html">Unhappy Numbers</a>.
%e A094406 The first term is a(0) = 4, the smallest number that is in the "unhappy number cycle" (4, 16, 37, 58, 89, 145, 42, 20) and therefore needs no steps to reach it.
%e A094406 The second term is a(1) = 2, because one iteration of the sum-of-squares-of-digits map A003132 it yields 2^2 = 4 which is in the unhappy number cycle.
%e A094406 The third term is a(3) = 11, because it is the smallest number to take two iterations of A003132 to reach first 1^2 + 1^2 = 2, then 2^2 = 4 which is in the unhappy number cycle.
%e A094406 a(3) = 15 is the fourth term because it's the smallest number requiring three iterations, 15 => 1^2 + 5^2 = 26 => 2^2 + 6^2 = 40 => 4^2 + 0^2 = 16, which is a member of the unhappy number cycle.
%Y A094406 Cf. A001273.
%K A094406 nonn,base,changed
%O A094406 0,1
%A A094406 _Sergio Pimentel_, Apr 30 2004
%E A094406 Edited by _Charles R Greathouse IV_, Aug 03 2010
%E A094406 Offset corrected by _M. F. Hasler_, Jul 04 2026
